{"id": "3666", 
"title": "Hungry code assist eats too much code", 
"description": "Under certain circumstances, the code assist feature in the IDE is consuming more code than intended. This can be observed with the following class:

public class X {
    void bar(X x) {
        baz(x.foo());
    }
    int foo() {
        return 5;
    }
    void baz(int i, int j) {}
}

To reproduce the issue:
1. Open the IDE and enable code assist
2. Use code assist while editing the 'bar' method
3. Add a parameter to the 'baz' call in 'bar'

Actual result: The code assist feature adds an extra 'foo()' method call resulting in 'baz(x.foo().foo())'

Expected result: It should only add the necessary parameter, resulting in 'baz(x.foo())'", 
"OB": "The code should be modified to only add the necessary parameter to the 'baz' call in 'bar'. The correct code would be:

public class X {
    void bar(X x) {
        baz(x.foo());
    }
    int foo() {
        return 5;
    }
    void baz(int i, int j) {}
}

I expect the code assist feature to behave as follows:
- When adding a parameter to the 'baz' call in 'bar', it should only add the parameter without adding any additional method calls.
", 
